# Language Preferences — [TEMPLATE]

> **Template.** Rename to `language.md` if you want to use it. Optional layer.

This rule defines what language(s) your AI agent should use in different contexts. If you don't fill it out, the AI defaults to the user's question language for replies and English for code.

## Communication

```
Reply to me in: [your preferred language — English, Spanish, Japanese, etc.]
Avoid: [languages or terms that are politically charged for you]
Tone: founder-to-founder / mentor / peer / etc.
```

Tone notes (optional):

- "Recommendations > options. 'Do X because Y' not 'here are 5 approaches.'"
- "No corporate language. Direct."
- "Patient and explanatory. I'm learning."

## Code

Standard convention (follow unless you have specific reason to deviate):

- **Code comments:** English (fewer tokens, more precise, broader collaboration)
- **System prompts (LLM-facing):** English (better model performance)
- **User-facing text** (UI, emails, etc.): your product's user language
- **Variable / function names:** English
- **Documentation:** English (or your team's working language)

## Examples

Some users go bilingual — Russian to user, English in code. Some keep everything in their native language. Some default to English everywhere.

The point is making it explicit so the AI doesn't switch unpredictably.

## How this gets loaded

Once renamed to `language.md`, reference from your main schema (`AGENTS.md`):

```markdown
## Communication
Read `agent-os/rules/language.md` for language preferences.
```
